At the end of the exchange, the Prague stock exchange swung in the negative
Following the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trade.
On Tuesday, from the start of the exchange, the Prague stock exchange resumed its fall from the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This is due to the fall in Wall Street stocks.
The market reaction to the result of the vote of the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilize the U.S. financial sector, is thus also perceptible in our country.
Falling stocks in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices managed, over the course of the day, to erase part of the losses.
The Hong Kong stock exchange Hang Seng index lost four percent during trading, but later wiped out part of the losses and reduced the drop to 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Chinese stock movement of the Hong Kong stock exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“The hesitation about the U.S. rescue action will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong’s monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries could be affected.
The bloodshed of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion Kčs).
The lawmakers rejected the call to support President George W. Bush’s project.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodshed on Monday and the main stock indices saw the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost seven percent, having experienced such a drop for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gives in: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banks
Leaders of the U.S. Congress and President George W. Bush’s government have agreed on a broader form of financial aid agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in negotiations on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion (about $12 trillion) of financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and submit it to vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the deal.
The support plan for the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Committee on Banking and Financial Regulation, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, as early as Wednesday, the plan should be submitted to the Senate for a priori vote.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor to revive financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which aid to markets can be effective, there will be a “disillusion.”
The plan must be effective.
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the shape that the package of measures for market stabilization should take," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
The final vote could be held on Sunday.
In the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government a final shape.
It is expected to buy up, from financial companies, non-selling real estate assets that result in significant losses for financial companies and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to continue, but I think we are there,” Paulson said.
A Signal for Asian Trade
The global financial crisis has a considerable impact on falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are making sure Congress reaches a final agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trading on Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the decision of Congress could affect Monday’s exchanges.
At the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two houses of the U.S. Congress will vote, or whether the negotiations are not likely to be blocked, at the last moment, by one issue or another.
Legislators hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount allocated to the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option to block the allocation of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of putting it in minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted of obtaining funds for the redemption of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, wasined.
“All work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to pass the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George W. Bush is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Reduction of gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on the accountability of the financial program, the protection of taxpayers against losses, the agreement on depreciation, the development of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
It should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also provides for aid for property owners, who have trouble paying.
The government should negotiate new levies in the case of mortgages it is going to redeem, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
