According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that we don't know what the mechanism and price will be for the repurchase of the problematic assets.
This point will be crucial in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week to the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not so important.
“It is much more important that congressmen agree, this week, that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, is most important at this time," Marek said.
A struggle pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We will advise you how to choose.
While almost all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems to result clearly that it is better to buy only a phone.
There are plenty of reasons to find an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for home a high-end expensive gramophone to put on Maxim Turbulenc’s new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason, for this to happen.
Now, if there are in your shelves packed vinyl discs, with art rock, jazz or blues, you are at least probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to put it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time with headsets bought for twenty crowns on the market.
Here are two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are able to do much more than just play music, but these are features unknown, of course, to most mobile phones.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephone calls and SMS sending, it is able to play music and movies, record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, up to serve for navigation.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grille meat and no television will take photos, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two recharges will be.
And reading music is one of the most important energy gains.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second recharger for work - this is true even for the more expensive devices.
There will be no problem for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of a recharge, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the less performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited portion of the devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
You can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to handle it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobile phones.
As for the players, you do not need, except for the exception (iPod), any software.
Simply fill the music device from the computer via the USB connector.
Most mobile phones and players will create a media library by themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or the user’s judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobile devices have more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, you are primarily concerned with the life of the battery, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example, taking the tram, you just need any mobile reader MP3.
Almost all mobile phones are now capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile phone or player is able to play.
Everyone gets to play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will get up to you will have just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA music.
The AAC (format used by the firm Apple and its iPods), on the other hand, is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and purchase the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason to acquire a musical mobile.
The offer of the operators is unfortunately miserable and is limited, in most cases, to fast-made radio tubes.
Prices are also not the lowest.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile phones with them.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the phone out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which almost all mobile phones have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of mobile music is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three-four thousand crowns, one can have a already very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of an outlet for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best-equipped, also equipped with an entry for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone manages to secure the order of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transfer bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (the type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even considering the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can survive even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 SEK.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, instead choose specialized mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent MP3 control keys, which makes the ease of control closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose phones in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the most far in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Per
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering practically the same services as their Western European partners.
Despite this, we still lack something – a virtual operator, which would force traditional traders to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech carriers are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which that the price of a SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, also confirmed this.
This is why, following the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of a competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may sound paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, is choreographing with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network apparently no longer has much luck (by the way, now he would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has resulted in a considerable price drop, to which conventional operators had to react as well.
Nevertheless, even before the entrance of holiday troubles such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today in Britain were being heard.
Now, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February, we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Add that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high cost of building, operating andining the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good advertisement.
This activity is specifically aimed at men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would likely work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesman, doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service supply."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which would thus want to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not hidden, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We look forward to being able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner it will be the best.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a base."
And she adds: "It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited timeframe, we should have a concrete agreement right now.”
Vodafone instead focuses its attention on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says in this regard: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think means the most contribution from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The move of the mobile operators is easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a drop in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profits.
What is the point of creating such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to feel like thieves at the fair. The chicane that accompanied the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, at the time of the creation of the U:fon, was that of the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ web pages.
However, today, the U:fon is prepared to serve as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: “In addition, the competition in the mobile market has recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands.”
But given the attitude of mobile operators like this, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, in the face of this problem, he adopted his typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori shown sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS Department of Foreign Relations in response to our question.
Such a statement would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But from the side of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially as Kristián Chalupa adds: “In the overseas, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile phone services.”
However, pressuring the market to function fairly and lower prices is apparently not in the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concorde of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, whether this really is a coincidence, arises naturally.
Similarly, a strictly identical price of gasoline at all gas stations is probably due to the chance and to the harsh fight of competition.
“The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behavior in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and none therefore has a corresponding increased responsibility for their behavior on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even in the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is a relevant market analysis by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are apparently acting in a similar way.
Nevertheless, complaints from many stakeholders (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Bringing responsibility back to the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, with which the ÚOHS washes hands of the affair.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the new Telecommunications Act, which was recently adopted, failed to extend the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised an improvement of the situation.
This, the representatives of the ÚOHS must very well know, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can walk.
That said, the operation of a sort of pseudo-virtual operators, many in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile phone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Customized mobile phone services are provided by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
Pricing lists of these firms usually reach only elected members.
The magic turn consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who commands a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special (and other) price deals.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would be examining and that could result in the cessation of the collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the leaders of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is opposed to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them not negligible profits, and at the same time, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot dispose of it fully, in the way of ordinary customers of mobile operators.”
This is exactly what should seem strange in the ČTÚ.
There is also another question in the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively wide powers to be able to disclose such activity, and if it will not want to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
We are no longer the most expensive country.
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable drop in the price of services.
However, in virtually every country where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a too small or even too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
Now, it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up achieving the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are dealing with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is removed by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experience we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them in these cases.
But don’t throw the sleeve after the stroke.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear with us, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain impasse in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech National Anthem.
On the occasion of the Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, a choir interpretation and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech National Anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously told Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose to interpret the singers' solo versions with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers, as well as the choir, have a good diction, so that the words are well understood, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first sung in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (Theatre of States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of Savetiers), a Czech original play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet became naturally an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
