Prague public transport (MHD) will introduce chip in their ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be inscribed in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic voucher in their pocket.
Currently, the latter is accessible to about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day voucher (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and register it on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency), located at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to purchase coupons online on the websites of the Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will begin to use the online store may forever forget the checkpoints in the metro stations, where they had until now to impairing in long queues in order to get paper tickets.
In fact, they will buy their coupon over the internet and save it on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, there is a checkpoint with trained staff available to passengers, who will help interested parties with online purchases and, in addition, record the coupon they purchased on their card," said Martin Opatrný, a project spokesman.
Alongside libraries, it will also be possible to save electronic coupons on the Opencard in automatic distributors installed in the hallway of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, they remind the machines to compose tickets and passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
“Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty,” Opatrný added.
An automaton will control the coupon in the driver’s place
The machines that will operate from tomorrow are easy to use.
Just enter the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register on the card itself.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also around the city.
Namely, in the peripheral trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of central Bohemia to access the capital.
