Sudans call for U.S. referendum
In 1945, the Sudet Germans demanded that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This is derived from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudet Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This arises, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
In the letter, Germans from Český Krumlov beg the US president not to allow the "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and we want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the Šumava cares."
Given that the reunification with Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only brutality, reckless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take the Šumava protectorate into his hands for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has contributed in no way to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter-million of its inhabitants," the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the “Czech oppressors.”
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of postwar history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Sudet Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans at least had to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would obtain some kind of autonomy for the Sudets.
Others thought they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from České Budějovice, engaged in the Navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once back home, the Czech would be beneficial to them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war estimated, according to him, that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
