Olmert would return almost all the occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli provisional government, voted for the return of virtually all territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
"We must reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, or even all," Olmert told the daily.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), because without it, peace will not be made," he added.
He admits that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Whoever wants security in Jerusalem, and especially does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as it happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert said, referring to the two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens were wounded.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historic sites" located inside the Old Town.
“Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
This will not work,” he said later.
Retreat of the Golan Heights
Olmert also supported Israel’s withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he said is an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace deal with Syria.
However, this would also require some efforts from Damascus.
"I am not proposing to conclude peace with Syria on the basis of a withdrawal from the Golan," he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to give up their current relations with Iran; they will have to give up their relationship with Hezbollah (the Shiite movement); they will have to give up their constant support for terrorism from Hamas (the Shiite movement), Al-Qaeda (the terrorist network), as well as Jihad (the Holy War) in Iraq," he said.
Questions arising after the accident: Are stewards in the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long distance car is prohibited
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency bus company near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the journey.
"If one wanted to comply with the law strictly and formally, the activity of a steward is contrary to the road traffic law," said Transport Ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the road of the bus.
At that time, the girl was sadly sitting next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat in the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake suddenly, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the bus is under its technical data equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing seat equipment is not approved, passengers must remain sitting.
Student Agency long-distance buses do not have standing seats; which was confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by the company director Radim Jančura.
"This is a matter that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at first, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got that passengers can go to the toilet during the trip provided they have their own seat," he said.
The law ignores the steward.
"There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of a steward - no legal prescription deals with this role.
On the other hand, no legal prescription also prohibits the carrier from offering services.
The road transport law only knows the term vehicle receiver; it does not define his rights and duties," adds with more ambiguity the spokesman Hanzelka.
Josef Pokorný, director of the Department of Road Vehicle Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
“It all depends on whether the bus has permission to offer standing seats in its homologation.
Everything lies in it,” he said.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing seats and a limited maximum speed, interurban with standing seats and a higher allowed speed and long-distance buses without standing seats with the highest allowed maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in a plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert at BESIP (Road Traffic Safety) on safety in transportation, does not see the displacement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"With regular traffic, there is no danger.The situation can be compared to that of service in airplanes.
There, too, it’s not sure when a turbulence will occur and the hostess of the air may hit her head.”
Now, in the event that the bus would have brakes abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
Just like in a bus or tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of the stewards through internal regulations," he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the problem is not resolved.
Jančura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only bus carrier to offer stewards services.
He hired two hundred.
Even after this accident, the manager does not regard their profession as a risky profession.
“H, as soon as I have the impression that this is a risky profession, I will remove it.
Passengers can get their coffee and their diary on board.
This would also reduce costs,” he said.
The safety concern is the reason that the absence of stewards in its vehicles is given by the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, who ensures, compared with SA, a very small number of lines.
“We don’t have hostesses, we’ve been opposed from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end up in a fatal accident," he told Týden.cz a year ago.
A huge tragedy has occurred.
A young hostess from the Plzeň region, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop lane without using a flash and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid him by means of a sudden manoeuvre, but he struck him by his right side.
Jančura denies that the two seats reserved for the stewards' rest have been sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company has filed a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but in terms of financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
A change in the law, which has been being drafted for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide clarifications on the travel of stewards on board the bus.
“We have not come to any conclusions on this issue.
Honestly speaking, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the point system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers," said Hanzelka, adding that the control of the safety of buses is under the authority of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
