Shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the federal finance minister insisted just a few weeks ago.
What a fortune that the politician used the word 'relatively' and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate finance firm Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains a billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person in confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are issued up to a sum of 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction it would be entitled to.
The money comes from private banks as well as public banks.
In the background, it is the Depfa subsidiary that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself very short-term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since due to mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, and the equity ratio had also slightly decreased from 1.6 percent to 1.45 percent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions fell to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, while profits from the allocation of certain credits and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit transactions fell from more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
And it was only thanks to the significant profits derived from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the Tax Procedures and Commercial Acquisitions Book for Konzern companies that the profit deficit of approximately 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially badly speculated on industrial real estate loans, which had later been affiliated with the bank Aareal.
Because conventional state financing was not cost-effective enough, Depfa was then more engaged in infrastructure projects and in the financing of private-state joint projects (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate must carry out amortizations which should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group’s gains and losses, which remains yet quite blurred.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had already been cut to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions that depend on refinancing on the interbank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks again slowed considerably, with banks accumulating liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term means of refinancing annually for a portion – approximately €50 billion – of all the credits of the Depfa.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing needs are covered with medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of operation at the moment.
Other sources say refinancing will be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman of the Board of Directors Georg Funke, however, explained that the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to the financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for the Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the market capability of the Hypo Real Group is now ensured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors can only hope.
However, given the dynamics and insurmountability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
The opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest communications, still at the doors of insolvency on Sunday at the end of the evening, this rescue, at least provisional, will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The price of the stock fell from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
The bond prices, on the other hand, go well.
While the first-tier debt has barely moved, the second-tier loan rates are flattening.
The most affected are mainly the investment funds of the former Württemberg subsidiary Hypo and those of course that have a lifetime beyond 2009.
The bonds of the bank Hypo Real Estate previously seemed to be an alternative speculative investment, now their value must be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institute itself that brought the crisis into the institution by the purchase of the bank Depfa.
As long as issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, we can assume a resorption of the downturns in time.
Or it will happen what no one dares to expect at the moment – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed rumors of partial nationalization, the probability that was approaching certainty has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia primarily to long-term creditors on the decision whether or not they should separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn on to constitute a postponement of losses for the coming years on the next automatically levied capital income tax.
