Rats also have emotions.
A rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that he feels fear too?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as us?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without which I or anyone else has so far been able to prove it, just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we penetrate into terrain hardly practicable because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is faced with danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, runs away or attacks.
Humans behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in direction and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other beings.
So at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being even differs from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might lie in the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, is neither measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is beside another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine animal consciousness processes without considering their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies on primate short-term memory, with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in achieving visualization.
But what does this mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as body reactions) captures vivid memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute them to others than ourselves.
Conversely, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the areas of body sensation of the cortex and brain trunk, just like Jaak Pankseep who, however, focuses more on the brain trunk.
Since this network hasn’t changed much during human evolution, it might quite participated in cross-sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I think it is undetectable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and rats is likely to be felt as fear in both cases: how could one verify whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Surely, the nerve comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain trunks, while cockroaches don’t even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the source of sensations?
And even if we could prove this to humans, how could we prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I do not know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and on language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is punching on the nervous plane in so far as the same thing is judged in rats and in humans.
