Bilingual Debate: Immersion in the English Language
In this part of the Education Supervision Program, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidate’s position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a former member of California Studies, and former director of the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think.
Attracting favors from Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are an interesting example of this.
Obama’s campaign emphasizes that “Afro-American and Latino students are less likely to graduate than white students.”
To combat these differences, Mr. Obama’s education program supports, among many other subjects, “bilingual transitional education” for those who learn English.
However, the question that arises for Obama is whether his desire to bilingual education that advocates classroom instruction in languages other than English goes beyond his interest in eliminating differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in the eastern Los Angeles County.
The students of this school are mostly Hispanic, and low-income.
More than one-third of the students, many newcomers, study English.
Among CM1 students, 100% passed the 2008 State Math Examination, expert level.
Similarly, almost 93% of students passed the English-Language-Art exam
This incredible success was achieved thanks to a different ingredient than that promoted by Mr. Obama.
Sixth Street is based on analysis, practice, constant assessment of capabilities and an exemplary attitude.
In addition, and this is an example that Mr. Obama could copy, says Linda Mikels, head of Sixth Street, this school has introduced the instruction of the English language "full immersion".
Total immersion in English focuses on the almost constant use of English in instruction.
Melle Mikels, opposed to bilingual education, told me “we had a huge success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, 12 months later, if you went without his class, you would have had no chance of identifying him.”
“It works,” she observes, “it worked for us.”
Shouldn’t Mr. Obama take the example of Sixth Street Prep and replicate it in other schools that are mostly Hispanic students learning English?
The excellent results of this school speak for themselves; but the education policies within its party (the National Education Associations have long supported bilingual education) and its enormous support for bilingual education obscure the forecast of Mr. Obama’s response.
Although he is in favour of immigrants learning English, Mr. Obama recently considered this issue insignificant, when he proclaimed that we must all stop polemizing about the wording of English-language laws.
Instead, he said, “You have to make sure your child speaks Spanish.”
If Mr. Obama really wants to eliminate differences, then he should carefully consider the models of education that work, rather than despise them or consider them insignificant.
Oil Price Decline Following New World Economic Worries
Oil prices dropped sharply on Monday as people fear the bailout plan will fail to bring the economy back to life.
Oil futures operations fell 7 percent to $99.80 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange during the sale this morning.
Prices have dropped by more than $20 a barrel since Monday.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by financial unrest on Wall Street, as well as by two powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After experiencing a rise of $145.29 per barrel in July, prices fell to almost $90 per barrel this month, before rebounding again in view of deep uncertainty in the financial markets.
Investors are once again concerned on Monday despite the deal on the bailout plan, the largest in history, concluded this weekend by Congress leaders.
The news has been mitigated by recent concerns that the crisis will be lasting.
In the very latest episode of this financial disaster," Citygroup will buy the banking operations of the Wachovia Corporation, the government said on Monday.
At the same time, the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg nationalized the European financial conglomerate, Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the frenetic negotiations this weekend, concluded with the bailout agreement, "seemingly failed to revive the market."
As the economic situation deteriorates, demand for raw materials, including oil, is expected to slow down.
“The outlook for global equity, interest rates and exchange markets has become uncertain,” Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a letter to their investors.
“We believe that raw materials will not escape this contagion.
“When it comes to raw materials, our most pressing concern is to understand how far the U.S. virus would spread globally and in China in particular.”
The bank's analysts lowered their forecasts for next year, given the fall in oil consumption due to the slowing economic growth, so were forced to lower by 20 percent, the forecast of oil and gas prices for 2009.
