In a City Apart, the Pride and the Trials of the Dark Life
Hidden in the development of its immense park, a few miles from the sunny, bright and giant Orlando, is a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, the first entirely black city to be integrated, Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, this description she made in 1935, is no longer so simple to do today."The city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of goyaves, two schools and no prison."
It has become a pilgrimage town.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the Zora Festival, which is held every year in Eatonville, to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous Harlem Renaissance writer.
And in various ways, the city it describes—has become tourist thanks to its inclusion in the Florida Tourist Guide published by The Depression—era Federal Writers’ Project—is still a place apart.
She is as independent, worthy, and private as she was in the 1930s when Hurston told us that the rural black population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knowing us so little, does not know what he is losing."
Even if this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has in turn invoked an open dialogue on the topic of race, many here remain cautious of the foreign gaze.
“We are very cautious about how to tell the story,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a resident ever and the oldest parishioner in the city.
“It has to be consistent with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and fighting.
It represents both a historic model of black power-taking as well as a community of 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of southern black rural culture—sometimes despised, other times acclaimed—reminiscent of the birth of American slavery.
That would explain why residents are both proud and protective.
Interest in the image of Eatonville was born with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her hometown to the world through sincere, dialect-filled books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide turned this city, just at the exit of Route 17, into a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida, ending up in a chapter of dark history and human drama.
As bold as a big box in life as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was subsequently split into several private sections.
“Crossing the road on the left,” she writes, “you’ll find the modern brown-and-white public school, with its gardens and those well-preserved playgrounds that Howard Miller has always cared for, though he barely knows how to read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash’s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds as well as anything that can serve passers.”
So, in just a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, re-marriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not so.
It wasn’t a portrait that everyone liked.
Zora described the reality well," said Ella Dinkins, 90 years old, one of Johnson's young girls that Hurston immortalized, citing the colorless songs performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: “Some people didn’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered as a vivid and eccentric person, who frequently returned after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town without warning, on board a large Chevrolet, a cigarette in his mouth and wore pants here, where even today, we are proud of traditional clothes.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin told, while many laughed at her.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” he said.
But he added, swinging in his chair from the rear patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was baptized, that “she never stayed too long.”
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a star of literature, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in any tomb, in Fort Pierce, Fla, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no big commemoration, no plaque for the general public.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy it offered to the world," said Valérie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A crucial moment occurred in the 1980s.
Officials in Orange County wanted to make a five-way highway pass through the city, to replace the Boulevard Kennedy, the main two-way street of the community.
The development of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 to the western corner of the city.
The proposal was made while Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period of its history.
Forced integration, among so many other things, has put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the dispute over mixing races led hatred to the gates of the community.
“At that time, a bunch of white youths came and threw oranges or objects at the people sitting on the side,” Franklin said.
“A woman has died.”
They threw a straw from their car.”
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration, defining his decision in Brown v. Board of Education "insulting rather than glorifying my race."
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, although positive in some aspects, has diluted Eatonville’s cohesion and weakened youth confidence.
“Black children used to be kissed—I remember—we kissed our master in the morning, and also in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and chief director of the Eatonville Community Safeguard, a non-profit group.
This lasted, she added, until the time when teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You don't kiss your white teacher because he's white - I mean there's a line of cultural demarcation here," said Melle Nathiri.
Civil rights, on the other hand, have created room for many other Zora Neale Hurston – black writers, actors and artists who have gone beyond prejudice, like her, armed with joyful self-confidence and lines of conduct such as: “How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!”
It exceeds me.”
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited the anonymous tomb of Hurston and began struggling to revive her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography on Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a true best-seller, reintroduced her to the American canons.
The highway project came just at the time when Eatonville’s most famous girl had regained its appeal.
And this time, Hurston’s old neighbors see her as a savior.
The community began organizing a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences this highway would have.
Hundreds of fans came to the opening of the festival two years later, and many come back in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the council rejected the proposal for the highway.
"The fiasco of the five-way highway, extremely fast, a real civic pride," said Melle.
Melle Boyd summarized it all by stating that “Zora saved Eatonville.”
The victory over the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents began to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been classified as a historic city since 1998.
A mono-theme library (renamed of course Hurston) opened in 2006 on a magnificent Kennedy Boulevard, repaired.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back street on a rainy summer day, as small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(There are 90 percent of black people now.)
Foreigners who come to discover the history of Eatonville, its reason for being, are still treated with caution.
Permission must be sought for most interviews, and certain things—such as the walls of the old church in Eatonville, painted by the white man, illustrating black men in the fields—are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Melle Jones, a brave teacher who has a weakness for bright red, are always afraid that their island community will be well understood.
However, given the expansion of Hurston festival, a certain level of local pride has emerged.
Young people in particular tend to regard Eatonville as Hurston considered his entire race: beautiful, problematic and everything, neither better nor worse, but also proud, creative, hardworking, crazy and mixed than other ethnic and racial groups in America.
Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police, who need additional forces.
And even for the younger, like the 11-year-old Alondra and Alexia Kenon, twins from Winter Park, they seem to have learned the Eatonville description correctly.
“Most people, who pass through this area there, will think, ‘Oh, this city has nothing compared to others,’” Alondra Kenon said after the Mass last Sunday.
But if you stop and take the time to contemplate history, it’s a very beautiful city.”
