"I photograph the master outside the stage to capture elements of his character." - Günther Bauer - Photographer
No clothes, no other clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
The other is the person.
They are inseparable except in the intimacy, in those moments unknown to the general public, where intimate gestures and stolen gaze are discovered by artists who don’t care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer blends in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few stages with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the peculiar iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, growing every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed “on the street” are artists able to convey on stage passion, sadness, joy ... captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists, you don’t have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and character.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars.”
With the "Cant populaire des Mines" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a digital camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, reminds of classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day."
It’s not about dance or singing in itself, but about the artist’s personality and character that captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has transformed into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits displayed in the gallery.
Bauer’s passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the “Portraits of old sportsmen” (“SportARTproject”).
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing people's portraits, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In photography, portrait is the most difficult kind.
You find yourself in front of people, characters you sometimes don’t know or who leave you just a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco entitled "Flamenco - people" is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of Rua de la Mata (route parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16 next year.
