Speaking while sleeping
Some children talk at night.
I’m not referring to those who wake up very awake and tell us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk during their sleep.
The first time it happens, you may be surprised, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
This is a benign sleep disturbance called somnilochia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, there are more than one who talks during the night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (piping in bed) or somnambulism, but this is not always the case.
As we said before, they can also be associated with very high fever, stressful situations or over-excitation.
This is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a small quiet voice, with isolated words, whispers or, on the contrary, with screams, crying, long speeches ...
In the event that somnilochia becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to obtain an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a benign impairment, which is why there is no treatment unless it is related to another sleep impairment that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to bed.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
