The Blood Again Safe
Héma-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the world’s safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And most importantly, it regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, headed by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was late to file his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” Dr. Decary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Thanks to efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Decary keeps in mind that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the outbreak of many cases of the human form of the mad cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then relyed on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when one does not know and a serious disease may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are instituted.
In April 1999, people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980 were refused blood.
However, a few years ago, it was demonstrated without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle applied makes sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have shortened the mute period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors are infected without knowing and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health,” says Héma-Québec’s chief executive.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year appeared on the island of Réunion the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Decary before stressing that in addition to a security supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
“The demands are increasing because the population is ageing.
As anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need recharge in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which consists on average of only 3% of Quebecans eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country with malaria, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3% we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but most importantly to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
With today’s life so busy, one rarely finds time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye globules, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to collect more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing for transplants early next year,” says Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
