For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defense and fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers backed by the bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will shake up the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
