Wall Street rescue operation: Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides for: better control by elected members of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at wages paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective on the markets,” Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
"Everything has been done in such a way as to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing Wall Street crisis," she said.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions on American daily lives will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned to a sprint in recent hours due to fears of the effect a new failure would have on investors’ mood.
The deadline agreed was the opening of the markets this morning.
Associated with late negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather favorable to the agreement, but nevertheless expressed their dissatisfaction that one was forced to get to this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that aimed at allowing owners to keep their homes and that on the salary of executives of companies rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope it does."
“The big lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky, and unsold debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the burst of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprimes) before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and resulting in a liquidity freeze and banking and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican-elected voters who overturned the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since the Democrats accepted that some of the "toxic" assets of companies in trouble are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added stating that if the government had to bear losses for five years with this program, it could set up new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to which another $100 billion may be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be approved by another congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the rescued companies that will pay him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to sell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and start-up allowances paid to executives of affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
Votes have risen yesterday against the bill, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Obviously, Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's finance committee, told voters.
“We have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
It’s not about benefiting taxpayers.”
Animating a small group in Congress nicknamed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to tell us: we are asking Congress not to rush and carefully consider the path to take,” he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
Following an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for €11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was renouncing to acquire its competitor in the midst of the shipwreck since it lost €2.9 billion in the U.S. mortgage crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and 10 largest insurance companies.
“It’s not lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
In exchange, you get back voting rights in the bank and influence.
It’s just something that savers and households appreciate now that the times are uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank misled by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all current loans from the bank Bradford and Bringley, including more than $41 billion ($75.5 billion) in real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander has announced that it will buy the bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
