What could Zuschlag &amp; Company do in their facturing factory?
In the near future, on 8 October, hearing on the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, permanently and regularly, having caused significant damage.
According to the prosecutor’s office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by fake invoices.
The state and municipal money, about 65 million HUF in total, went to the box office of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and some people’s pockets.
Their method, also made public by the authorities in charge of the investigation, was to raise the money from subsidies obtained by issuing bills of fees, behind which no actual service was provided and thus the associations never met their commitments.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were false.
For the latter, they obtained bill books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps at Kiskunhalas.
The names of companies to be included in the invoices were decided, inter alia, during the tour in the northern province of Lake Balaton, conducted by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he had to identify pensions and restaurants.
For his personal expenses, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among other things, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital for access to grants.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "screening circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two bills issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place provided the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice issued on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which subsequently will be named Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért, was full of form and substance errors.
One pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three bedrooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there.
Facturers with overwhelming imagination also fell into excess when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, which also belongs to the Horeca sector.In their accounting, neither Jobb Jövőért nor Hoppá’s name appeared, according to information given to the prosecutor’s office.
Győző Farkas, the company’s manager, told the website hvg.hu that when the prosecutor’s office summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were fake documents.
"Our company name and tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people were staying there, did not fit either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time.”
The zealous bill issuers also did not inquire about Budapest’s travel agencies, as part of their choice, but only organized trips abroad.So, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on cash bills, which is also contrary to the agency’s accounting practices.
Furthermore, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT to these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate for the four invoices issued on behalf of the Hotel Révfülöp on the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company’s services do not support a 25% VAT as indicated, but a 15% VAT.
The prosecution's investigation reveals that the "emitents" also made mistakes by mentioning the transport of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, given that its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it is also for form defects, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued on the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI.
Just as in the case of the company Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó sports stage, both of whom deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The counterfeiters also did not pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was supposed to have a meal at their home.
Deliberately issued invoices
Another category of invoicers is that of those who were fully aware that they were asked to issue fictitious invoices.
Esély Budapestért Alapítvány, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, issued an invoice to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért for a sum of four million HUF.
