No financial movements took place, as the issued invoices were subsequently cancelled, but the agencies avoided mentioning this in their accounts.
The next category of invoice issuing companies is that of companies directly linked to the accused.
Thus, the administrative delegate of the CEO of the company Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose headquarters was in Budapest, but where he was not found, was Ivan Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, these equipment were acquired by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which was in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov had also delivered documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to the order of the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to the Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he took their counter-value.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian Freemasons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
