The psychology of overpricing: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay a too high price.
These researches have attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (MRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain regions of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction of which an essential element is the overbidding of a third, the set located under the brain trunk, called the striatum, moved intensely when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the escape to the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, economists members of this group of researchers conducted financial surveillance analyses.
In these, three groups overpriced against one partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they thus made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they went out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received those $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money in case they lost the auction.
The difference between the two groups is that one group focused on victory, while the other group focused on failure.
Thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the player team "against failure" were willing to make higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These findings cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena seen at auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in the face of risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
Hundreds of miles of patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary are estimated, but only seven miles follow treatment.
The term hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms.Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and engendered diseases differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by general illness, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible yellowing develops on the skin and the white of the eye, the stool becomes brighter and the urine takes a darker color.
Worldwide, one million people die each year from the most severe form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know if they have the virus, because the pathogenic gene deliberately destroys liver cells.In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
The contamination rate is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooers.
Currently, 200 million people worldwide have chronic hepatitis C.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as you notice symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time.The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
World Hepatitis Day is celebrated on September 30th, and was first organised in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief would work as a kind of analgesic, which would already have helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more tolerable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing how much belief in God could influence human tolerance for pain.
As part of this least bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the suffering.
Through a human brain palpation technique, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brains responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university participate.
Specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electrochocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look sustainably at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci’s painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an IRM scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electrochocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed painting.
Catholics said that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt like they were “safe,” like someone “careful” and they “calmed down, and peace invaded them.”
When they saw the religious-themed painting, they 12% less pain than when they watched Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided you find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, the Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of these researches.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases it actually changes our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if we show the believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the vision of a better Virgin Mary result in better results?
