A young person can generally keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his music habits. Then he can link them to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also hold blogs, in which they automatically display their most recent photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While one can take note of many examples, such as the girlfriend who easily understands in sight the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or the company who fired one of his employees, only for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about the top management, one can be on one thing: the term privacy is totally to reconsider these days.
He who lives an online life is made up of what he shows about himself, and this is how one can define the principle hiding behind the behavior of today’s youth.
Who wants to hide something, or at least wants to try to bypass the monopoly of Google, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but at the same time, deliberately leaving no trace).
The number of people who, deliberately, do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them, is not the least. Google's online services, from text processing to image processing, to reading information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not attached to huge server parks and which do not assemble our best profile, having existed until today.
The public is waiting, without really hiding it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
