The smart car imitates the flight of the burgundy
Which method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle than the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
As for example, the bees.
In the stunning project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the whirling bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired robotic self-control system, type BR23C, which it equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flight, each bee constitutes its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell,” explained Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the brand’s research and development and technological public relations department.
The face-faced eye of the bee plays a primary role, as it is able to see in all directions, at a angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of a laser telemetry.
It identifies obstacles at a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns it into a avoidance manoeuvre.
The perception of the obstacle occurs in a fraction of a second.Then the mini auto robot, mimicking the bee's movements, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system at present, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t, the mini car robot’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for now the collision is considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place at a glance.
Unlike bees, the difference can not go up, down, or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotational movement, acceleration as well as slowing as manoeuvres available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a greater energy concentrate, which makes their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is instinctive intelligent response that is primary, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres.
We do not need a memory capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instantaneous avoidance.Nissan estimates that this system will be introduced in mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles on his way.
