On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill corresponding to the name of Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of the Year 2008.
On Saturday evening, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and to protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
Moreover, the program differs from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion should be spent at once, for the repurchase of securities involving dubious credits.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion sum can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after the law has been passed by Congress, probably Monday. This first amount will be used by the Treasury Secretary to buy dubious loans from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President’s discretion.
The program will be supervised by an independent body, in which the Chairman of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The second half of the 700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to set up a combined strategy: it will be able, at the same time, to buy dubious debt, mortgage and dubious mortgage securities, as well as other types of "toxic" debt.
Ministry officials said the purchases could take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to participate in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools at the origin of the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to predictable damages.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the tools needed to devote $700 billion to the financial system’s urgent needs, whether it’s large-scale repurchasing, insuring, or avoiding the risk of seeing the system leading to the collapse of one or another major financial institution.
"We will take the necessary measures, to be ready for the application of the law, as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank executives who are in bad positions and waiting for state aid can expect their starting compensation, simply called the overseas golden parachute, to be ceased by the government.
The salary ceiling is mentioned only in specific cases.In addition, the limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the company.
The ceiling principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys as part of an auction, they will levy a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank chairman retires.
Immediately after the repurchase of questionable debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not exaggerated.
In order for the picture to be complete, it must still be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The ceiling applies only to new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in U.S. history that legal ceilings will be in place on the appointments of general directors, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the House Committee on Financial Services.
In addition, the state provides itself with a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan.In this way, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even be winning in the business as soon as the economy and with it the saved banks fall back on their feet.
The bill states that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal that will decide on how losses will be reimbursed to taxpayers, starting from the financial sector.
On both sides, there were obviously those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
It’s not for this reason that American citizens have mandated us, this doesn’t protect taxpayers’ dollars,” said California Republican MP Darrell Issa.
