Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, according to the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they fell by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month, and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing sectors experienced only a slight increase of the order of 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and shoe manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with first place, the manufacturing of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then the production of shoes with a monthly increase of 2.5 percent.
The higher levels of prices for plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the product and chemical manufacturing sector (1,6 percent).
The deflation resulted in oil processing (1,4 percent), machinery and electrical appliance manufacturing (0.9 percent), as well as a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 percent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing activities remained unchanged.
Other sectors of the processing industry registered an increase, ranging from 0.2 percent to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in the national industrial exploitation, prices suffered a 0.3 percent rise in August, mainly due to the effect of the rise in gas price imposed by the authorities since July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, it was the oil processing sector that experienced the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 percent, while in the important food, beverage and tobacco production sector, prices increased by 11 percent.
Prices dropped in the textile and textile manufacturing sectors (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 percent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices increased between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supplies sectors surged by 18.7 percent over the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the profit-on-investment initiators that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7%).
In the sectors of consumer goods production, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while those in the sectors of energy and materials for subsequent processing saw no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase was observed in the sectors of production of energy and materials for subsequent processing (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 percent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a 1.4 percent decrease.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 percent over 12 months.
Within a month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro, and by 7.1 percent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
