MP3 player pointing the finger, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to full-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement released in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
The study found that 5-10% of those who listen to full-volume music using portable music devices for at least 5 years, for more than an hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent hearing loss.
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use mobile music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“According to scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
In addition, we need to review existing control systems in view of the scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies.”
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
Scientists confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
This data can be greatly limited by using solutions such as reducing noise exposure levels and duration.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, are exceeding the current limits on the maximum permitted noise level at work.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for prolonged periods of time risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
