In the United States as well as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena of some time ago, to the point that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual state-sovereign category, in relation to a sort of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, of course, close relations with the outside world, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balances of people and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for who governs it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be global economically, but politically, it is almost only national here.
Political internationalization really seems out of play, or does not have much to say: the obvious proof is provided to us by the European Union that, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, does not manage to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, plans for rescue and relief, new rules, and above all a love of credit: when one goes through a difficult period, there are only the states who possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements of which no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the state-nation crisis is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, when we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that the globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized one by one, that our future will, on the contrary, have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather insignificant things such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can be transported from one place to another on earth, but which are absolutely connected to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, he who is sovereign has more cards than he who is not, that is, he who is unlucky to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow zone.
And besides, something even deeper, in a sense even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of distance that tends to involve the whole class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have at the same time, and to be increasingly foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
