Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, the cities remove the historical halls.
Historic cinemas are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinema is a blind city, it is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the province cities,
The process of the marginalization of the cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multisales, and the death of the consumption of the monosales in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that appears to us inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical and memorable places, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of road and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way to live the cinema, lost may be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of traditional type have closed, and it is the halls of the major cities that have paid the most: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romana is at the forefront with 82 lost mono cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilie-Romagne.
"The Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, chairman of the ANEC, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequentors are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplex.
Not to mention the failed credit deliberation in favor of merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the mono cinemas halls of the historic centers and the periphery.
Among the normatives envisaged are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is obvious, however, that in order to counter the superpower of the multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto, or Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side to not see the panels blackened by dust.
