Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colosses like Chevron have placed their eyes, and now are trying to put their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the ecologists and the new rise of oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of global electricity needs could be covered by ocean wave operating systems.
That would be twice as much as nuclear power plants produce.
In addition, there will be streams and tide.
